The paper proposes a framework for measuring intelligence in machine learning models without relying on labeled datasets, which is a common problem in the field of machine learning. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of "cs.LG" (Machine Learning), which is the most relevant sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of digital ledgers and competition for connectivity in the network, which are related to the sub-categories of "cs.DC" (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) and "cs.SI" (Social and Information Networks). The paper also discusses the use of gradient descent, which is a common optimization technique used in machine learning, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of "cs.AI" (Artificial Intelligence) and "cs.NE" (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
